<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-278-372  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 278 372.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  March 26 1990 v12 n13 p43(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Voice recognition: still a long way to go. (includes relatedarticles on Dragon System's voice typewriter, and voicerecognition systems used in hospital emergency rooms)</TITLE><AUTHOR>LaPlante, Alice.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Voice recognition has been one of the most interesting andpromising technologies in the computer field for years.andP;  Theproblem is that the technology still remains just that,interesting and promising, with no real breakthroughs on thehorizon.andP;  The main obstacles to voice recognition are thepainfully slow speed the user must speak at, and the high errorrate which is returned.andP;  The existing products are currentlytargeted at small, niche markets like brokerage houses and themedical industry, where only a limited vocabulary is required.andO;Some analysts believe that true voice recognition machines arestill five to 10 years away, while others say voice recognitionwill be the startling new technology that will create a new boomin microcomputer sales.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Voice RecognitionProduct DevelopmentState-of-the-ArtIndustry AnalysisResearch and DevelopmentApplicationsOutlook.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>